Behavior.name: Behavior
Behavior.description:
This is a template for a Behavior. A Behavior is a modular bit of code that invokes
a common pattern of actions on an object. Examples are giving an item eight-directional
movement, having an object follow another object, etc. Cutie already comes with a variety
of Behaviors, but if you'd like to build one yourself, simply override the methods described
here. *Note: This is just a template. You should never actually create an instance of this
class - it won't do anything.*

params.name: props
params.description: The properties passed in to the Behavior.

props.description: The object to render on a fire.

props.description:

props.description:

                                       cartesian positive x axis and degrees rotate counter-clockwise up from this x axis.

props.description: The keycode to be used for firing.

props.description: The delay in seconds between shots.

props.description: If set to true, use a mouse click to fire. If false the key will be set to fireKey.

props.description: If set, firing will be continuous while key/mouse is pressed.

cutie.name: cutie
cutie.description: # Cutiepa2D.js Cutiepa2D (pronounced cutie-patootie) is a wrapper for CreateJS. Its purpose is to make developing 2D games in javascript dead simple. It extends CreateJS with additional functionality and structure while still allowing you to access all of CreateJS's existing utilities. We think it's quite cute, and we hope you do too. ## Download Grab it here! **[Download](../../build/cutiepa2d.js)** ## Getting Started After downloading cutie, include it in your ```index.html```. You'll also have to run a local server in order to get image loading to work. I recommend [XAMMP](http://www.apachefriends.org/index.html) to get started. After that, you should be good to go! We have some examples in the [repo](https://github.com/greysonp/cutiepa2d), but we'll be writing proper tutorials (as well as expanding functionality) in the coming days. ## Getting it on Your Phone Testing in the browser is cool, but testing on your phone/tablet is even cooler. Thankfully, there's an awesome framework out there called CocoonJS that makes this dead-simple. First, they're framework converts your javascript canvas code to fast-performing WebGL code. But one of the coolest parts is that they have an app that you install on your iPhone/Android device that will allow you to literally copy your game files to your phone and play them. You don't even need a developer license on iOS! Very cool stuff. For a tutorial on using the app, check out [this page](http://support.ludei.com/hc/en-us/articles/201048463-How-to-use). ## Brought to You By * [greysonp](https://github.com/greysonp) * [MaybeNot](https://github.com/MaybeNot) * [stephenrlouie](https://github.com/stephenrlouie)

props.name: name
props.description: An array of the names of groups which interact with this collision group. "*" indicates all registered groups.

props.name: handler
props.description:
A collision handler to be called when an object of this group collides with an object in the group specified in the name array.
                                                It will have the signature (obj1, obj2, rect). obj1 is the first object involved in the collision. 
                                                obj2 is the second object involved in the collision. rect is the rectangular area representing the intersection between the objects.

classitems.description: Starts the game.
classitems.name: start

params.name: scene
params.description: The scene to start the game with.

params.name: props
params.description: A series of properties that affects the overall game and how the scene is set.

props.name: canvasId
props.description: The id of the canvas element you want to display your game in.

props.name: preloadScenes
props.description:
Which additional scenes to preload when you load this scene. 
                                              The progress bar for this scene will be representative of this 
                                              list's preload progress.

props.name: debugFPS
props.description:
A set of options related to showing the frames per second (FPS) on-screen
                                     for debug purposes.

props.name: size
props.description: The size of the FPS text. You must include units.

props.name: color
props.description: The color of the FPS text. Any valid CSS color should work.

props.name: updateInterval
props.description:
How often the FPS should update. Making the update interval too
                                                     short will just make the number unreadable (it'll change too fast).

props.name: scaleType
props.description: How you want the canvas to scale in the window. Does not impact the in-game with and height.
